<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1505,1725]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,372,1505,1531]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Etymology:—</emphasis>
Named for Professor Anne Bruneau of University of Montreal, 
<collectingCountry box="[1131,1223,1505,1531]" name="Canada" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Canada</collectingCountry>
. She has been the leading authority in 
<taxonomicName box="[390,591,1544,1570]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Caesalpinioideae">Caesalpinioideae</taxonomicName>
phylogenetics for over a decade. Her work and that of her students has led to the establishment of a phylogenetic framework for the subfamily creating a firm foundation on which studies of smaller taxonomic breadth such as this can rest. Bruneau made several collections of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mackinder &amp; Wieringa" baseAuthorityName="Oliver" baseAuthorityYear="1871" box="[1281,1436,1621,1647]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Annea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="afzelii">
<emphasis box="[1281,1436,1621,1647]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Annea afzelii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
during fieldwork in 
<collectingCountry box="[398,524,1660,1686]" name="Cameroon" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
in 1996, one of which was used in the preparation of the illustration of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mackinder &amp; Wieringa" baseAuthorityName="Oliver" baseAuthorityYear="1871" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Annea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="afzelii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">A. afzelii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
presented in this paper.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
